author: @scarletovergods
text: In my view we, as humans, are suffering from what I would call a humancentric model of AI. Everybody seems to think intelligence means that one can make decisions and perform activities similar to the ones we make in our everyday life. Like driving a car, holding a meaningful conversation, recognizing objects etc. But in my view those abilities are very human-specific, the same way decisions Deep Blue made are very chess-specific. In order to have human AI a computer would have to develop millions of small human-specific 'intelligences' and then manage them with other 'intelligences' . For example reading is a very specific ability that only humans have and you could easily imagine intelligent entities going about their day without it. And that's true with almost anything we do. So going back to my main point people will soon realize that teaching computers how to behave like we do we would need to teach them how to do millions of very small and specific things (color-detection, recognizing facial expressions, pondering free will etc) instead of finding one key idea that opens all the doors.  And so another AI winter is coming...  If you could comment my view on AI that would be awesome :)
